'''The Oaths Act 1888''' (51 & 52 Vict. c.46) was an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] which set out provisions whereby the [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)|oath of allegiance]] taken to the Sovereign may be [[Affirmation in law|solemnly affirmed]] rather than sworn to [[God]]. The Act was the culmination of a campaign by the noted atheist and secularist MP [[Charles Bradlaugh]] to take his seat. It was a significant piece of [[secularist]] legislation. The Act was consolidated and repealed by the [[Oaths Act 1978]].<ref>http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1978/19/introduction</ref>
